segments.text: Okay.
You like teamwork.
Yeah.
And you were seeing other people and step with you and you were attempting to do your part.
You were attempting to keep a straight line.
When you were working with artillery pieces, you were you wanted your part to be done when it needed to be done.
If you want a rammer or you were carrying a projectile or whatever.
I didn't want to buy weight.
I wanted to
If the breach needed opening, I didn't want the man with the projector waiting on me.
And these kind of things have always fascinated me.
I've always wanted to have my part done and nobody waiting on me.
I don't know whether that's one of the things that projects you out forward of others or whatever, but it was just something about it that was fascinating.
Now as a day student did you really feel part of the Corps or did in some ways you felt discriminated against?
No I missed a whole lot.
I missed a great deal.
Didn't live in the dormitory.
Got in on none of the hazing.
I hardly ever went in the dormitory unless I went to study with some fellow student.
So I know I missed a great deal of the core life, but farther up I went into the junior and senior year, of course I got more into the swing of it.
But I did, I'm sure I missed a great deal of it.
Some of it I guess I'm glad I missed.
Some of it that I could probably look back on with a lot of enjoyment.
Let's talk about your outfit.
Were you part of an outfit?
Yes.
What kind of training did you have?
Could you tell me about that?
You're talking about in the Corps?
Yeah.
They actually had day student organizations made up of day students.
Oh, day students.
So you were in a day student outfit.
That's right.
As I remember, that was only
freshman, sophomore years that they had the day student outfits.
I could, they could have been into the junior, senior, but I know the freshman year we were in what we called day students.
It was a Coast Artillery, one of the Coast Artillery units.
Oh, so you, so you got into Coast Artillery early then.
I started out in Coast Artillery and I was wondering how you got in now.
For the reason was, Seacoast Artillery, which I was in,
They, most all the calculations, the projections, the anticipated travel of the projectiles and all this was done mathematically, manually, with slide rules and this sort of thing.
But they encouraged engineers to get into the Coast Artillery, and particularly Seacoast.
Now, a lot of my classmates were in the Corps of Engineers,

which I probably should have been but I listened to the counselor or whoever and he says that Coast Artillery is a good place for engineers because of your mathematical training and education and whatnot so I got in Coast Artillery and it was
Oh I can't regret it a whole lot.
I had a lot of experiences that gave me a great deal of satisfaction but that's what I was in and that's why.
I didn't really know except that somebody said don't get in the infantry.
and that's the thing I thought I didn't want in but you know that's a pretty important area too.
So as a Coast Artillery Officer then would you be basically what we call fire control today?
I mean were you oriented toward hitting the targets then?
Well, are you talking about when I was on active duty?
Yeah, to begin with in your first first few years of active duty.
Is that what they tried to, let me rephrase that.
Is that what they tried to train you to do when you were here in the Corps?
Well, yes.
You had training in, you see, Coastal Artillery, our targets were vessels.
And the way they aimed and spotted them, unless it was what they used to call Case 3 where you couldn't see them, they were over the horizon,
Then it was all done by catching the ship here and here and you knew in so many seconds he'd be here.
That's the way we aimed.
Now if he was over the horizon with the big guns then it had to be some more calculations but that's the type of thing that I'm talking about and then if the burst hit here
You knew you were short so many seconds, feet, and whatever, and you recalculated.
But that was all, that was the basic training of Coastal Artillery.
But when I got on active duty, the fact that I was an engineer, I was more directed toward surveying in baselines, establishing base end positions that had to be exactly measured,
They had to be exactly oriented.
And I took survey crews and did this sort of thing for the fire control batteries and people that had to occupy these.
And our spotting was done with a triangle, see, from these known points to this.
So I did a lot of surveying.
So, but it was...
So, yeah, it's a generally problem.
That's what it was.
That's fascinating.
For fixed coast artillery...

You had a fixed end here and a fixed end here with an absolute known distance on the base and that's right and then you had a you had a one line and two angles you always knew and so they could they could project so that was part of my duties for a good long while was establishing these things.
And what kind of training did you get down here at A&M in the court?
Well, I was, of course, along with all the rest of them.
We studied projectile travel, projectile variance due to various elements in the air and care of the guns.
Of course, a lot of leadership courses is all the services.
But it was mainly aimed toward being an artilleryman.
The first two years are pretty basic, reality's what you're in.
But a lot of the infantry tactics and parades are always fascinating.
I loved that parade.
I really did.
I used to love those parades out there at the university, you know, the final reviews and the Mother's Day reviews and all these things.
I loved those things.
After I got on active duty, I really liked the parade.
I did.
I sure did.
Why do you think that?
You like the unison?
That's right.
Again, it's seeing people executing commands, seeing people following orders, seeing people act in unison.
You know, everybody...
Everybody got to be in step.
If not, you sit, you know.
It's just, it's that regimentation, I guess.
You must love the Aggie band.
Oh, that's the greatest thing in the world.
It just tingles my spine, and I've seen it 10 million times.
That's incredible, isn't it?
Couldn't believe it when I saw it when I came down here.
Had you never seen it before?
Oh, I never have.
I might have had seen it on national television when they used to carry the Texas and the A&M games back when they played the Thanksgiving games, but now you don't see those on national television.
It's absolutely fascinating.
The farther up the line of command I got, I guess the more I enjoyed it.
Even after I got to be a brigadier general on the beach.
We always had a parade at some camp and we've had as many as, oh, at one time our unit had about 4,000 people in it.
We've been to camp with 3,000, 3,500.
That makes a pretty good parade.
But we always had a parade, sometimes and sometimes not.
Could you tell me about your colleagues in the Corps of Cadets, people that you went through?
I made some real good friends.
In fact, a lot of the ones, a lot of my senior, junior and senior and probably sophomore compadres, as I said a while ago, were called active youth at the same time.
There was a colonel who used to be our, we call him, War Department inspector.
Once a year, the War Department sent regular Army people down to inspect the units, the seniors and juniors, and I think mostly seniors and juniors, to evaluate the ROTC program.
I'm sure it's still done.
But this old colonel, I remember in particular, had been there a couple, three times.
And how he got picked to organize this Coastal Artillery Unit, I really don't know, because that's done through the War Department.
But he did, and apparently got the opportunity to select officers that he could call active duty.
But we were called almost a year before Pearl Harbor.
I got one of those early calls.
And he selected about 60% of us from A&M.
And gosh, I bet you there was half of my Coast Artillery class that got called to this unit.
So not only made the friends there, but had them for four years during World War II.
And right to this day, we still have a reunion of the World War II.
Oh, really?
How many are you?
Well, this past summer, there are more than we get together, but this past summer we had a reunion set.
There were, I guess, 16 of us that were going to go all the way to Myrtle Beach, South Carolina.
to be with one of our commanding officers, and he was taken to Walter Reed Hospital and subsequently died, so we had to call off the reunion.
But, well, I guess we were probably 17 or 18.
There still goes, every time we call or every time we've had a reunion, we've had about 21 reunions since World War II.
So, it was a
camaraderie that really did last.
So, you know.
That's tremendous.
It is, and it started right there in A&M.
Of course, they've got a spree decor out there that's, it never dies.
Anywhere you go, if there's an avian, you'll surface somewhere pretty quick.
Let's talk about leadership.
Did you have any position of leadership in the court?
Well, my senior year I was on the regimental staff, which I guess you'd say was

position leadership but I was not in the company ranks I was I was on the core staff I mean on the regimental staff I guess it was so uh that that's the first uh movement of uh out of the blind so to speak right so I was uh I thought I was proud of it oh your duties there

Oh not uh not significant it's more you felt I guess a sense of pride of being put there probably I had less duties than if I'd been in one of the companies as far as you know things to do but uh we we had some responsibilities of planning maneuvers and planning you know at summer camp

bivouacs and this sort of thing so there was there were some of the responsibilities that he would not have had just I guess down in the ranks now you meant let's talk about the things you liked and you disliked about the corps you've already mentioned that you like the uniform and you like the marching you like the parades you like the camaraderie any other things that you liked about the corps I always I always enjoyed
being around army officers, the regular army officers who were our supervisors.
Why?
Why?
Something about the military that I liked.
I liked, I guess, a lot of the ways they wore the uniform.
I liked to listen to some of the, of course, many of them were World War II, I mean, World War I,

and then the old sergeants that were the backbone that ran the army you know back in the peacetime days I guess is the amount of chatter and big stories they told and you know you took in all that stuff we were young and aggressive and
Nobody ever thought we'd go to war, I'm sure.
But I don't know.
There's just something about the military that fascinated me.
I enjoyed it.
I enjoyed being obedient to my superiors.
I enjoyed the opportunity, as I've said two or three times, when they gave you something to do,
to do it well.
I always like to do it well.
And the military lends itself to that more than civilian officers.
And I like people to be obedient.
I like people to take orders, and if they're proper and good, to carry them out to the nth degree.
So the military just lends itself to that sort of thing.
Over the years, I've availed myself of all the military schooling that I ever got an opportunity to go to, and I've been to a lot of them.
It's enjoyable.
That's the best description I can give.
Now, you said you liked some of the regular Army officers.
Any in particular that had an impact on you?
Well, I was in school when this Major General Moore was a commandant.
He was a full colonel at that time, who later was commanding Corregidor and was taken prisoner.
And his bearing and posture used to just fascinate me.
He was straight as a poker.

he came around he would talk to freshmen or sophomores or you know anybody that that wasn't what he did all the time but when you were out on drill you know it never did surprise you if he stopped and talked to you.
He was one of them in a major hill who was a Coastal Artillery Officer.
I don't know they were sort of idols as far as officers.
You'd say as far as, I mean, you'd go as far as saying that they were idols.
Yeah.
But I never dreamed ever going that high in the military.
Really?
No, I didn't.
Why do you think that is?
I don't know.
I just, I really never thought about this parallel career in the military at that point.
I don't think I really
I don't think I really aspired to it.
I guess it was so remote to think of World War II.
It was so remote to think of all the reserve possibilities that did develop.
It was just completely out of the realm of my aspirations, probably.
In fact, when I got called to World War II,
I assumed I'd be home in a year because I was called for a year.
War hadn't started and I left home I told them I'd be back in a year.
But as the thing went along and at the end of the year they kept the officers who were so-called more efficient the ones that were goal breaking and

we used to say that we were penalized for being more efficient because they gave us orders to go on and and they turned loose some of the guys that were they wanted to be there and that always seemed a little unfair to me at the time but I think you understand that that's right that's the way it is that's right that's right at the time we said you know if they goof off they're gonna get to go home you know it's kind of unfortunate in a way uh

in the service in that respect because when they get somebody that they can count on then they just overburden the guy with words at least I know from my experience in the enlisted corps but when they get somebody that goes wrong but then they don't even bother the guy that's what I'm trying to get rid of.
And that's where you let them get out.
Yeah but that that was a that was a strange thing we read it.
I don't think I'd have wanted to be the only one that got out because
The ones that got out, we said, you know, let them go.
We're not interested in them.
And if I'd have gone, I'd have had a feeling, you know, that they didn't really want me anyhow.
Down deep, you don't want to be left out.
Now, we've talked about things you liked about the car.
Anything you disliked?
Oh, I'm sure there was...

you know it's not something I guess I can put my hand on though at the time I'm sure there were times that I'd probably rather been doing something else than cleaning the gun or getting the cosmoline off the rifle or digging the slit trench or something like that but it went along with it but as far as having a particular dislike I don't think I had any dislikes
You know, there wasn't any, now that you think back on the Corps in the late 1930s, there weren't anything that you'd say, boy that should have been changed, it would have made it better.
I don't really think so.
It's uh, and I guess I'm comparing it to nowadays, it was so superior as far as I'm concerned, and the uh, the attitude that the fellas had,
Today, I mean, comparing it today, you think it was superior back in the 30s than today.
Well, I'm not that close to the core anymore, but a number of times you get the feeling that they just, some of them don't have the attitude of excellence that they used to have.
Oh, really?
Well, how do you get that feeling?
I don't really know.
And I think really...
I relate it to the military and I'm letting it spill off back to the Coral because I'm certain as I'm sitting here that the military doesn't have it.
The field ain't a vaccine.
We're going to talk about the military.
And I'm afraid that I let that
filter back to the core, and it may be unfair, but I love to see that core.
I love to watch them and all this.
I hope I'm wrong, but you know, sometimes you generalize when you shouldn't.
Do you think that the core had any effect on the fact that you became a leader?
Yeah.
How?
Well, you saw people, you saw people who were, who were moving out ahead.
You want something with me Lucille?
You saw people who were moving out ahead, you'd see people who, first thing you know they were company commanders, they were corps commanders, they were cadet colonels,
And when I see people that are excelling, I like to excel.
And I think it gave me a feeling of, well, here's the way you do it.
So it definitely had a place.
It also gave me a feeling of...
consideration of superiors, consideration of elders.
Well, didn't you have that consideration from your parents?
Yeah, but I'll tell you what, the military helped that.
Yes, I had a very great feeling of obedience to my parents, but the military, you saw it every day.
Somebody answered to everybody.
and I could see from the early stages that the military was built on obedience and being able to carry out orders and to fulfill your responsibility.
That's what the military is built on and that instilled with the background that I had then that instilled in me those things that
You know, I think today are absolutely essential to a person who's going to succeed.
A little interesting incident.
I was a real good friend of General Rutter's.
Do you know who General Rutter is?
Being with the highway department and the position I had, we had a lot of common problems with the university.
And I've been in many sessions with him personally.
I remember one time I was referring to him as Mr. Rutter.
I'd say, Mr. Rutter, so-and-so.
He said, I'd love for you to call me Earl.
He was a two-star general.
At that time, I was probably a full colonel.
He was several years my senior.
I told him, I said, Mr. Rutter, there's no way that I could call you Earl.
I said, first place, you're a senior to me in the military, and you're a senior to me in AIDS.
I've got to call you Mr. Utter.
He said, okay, but I just sent you to call me Earl.
I could no more have called him Earl than I could have flown out of this window.
Why didn't you call him General?
Well, at that time, he was president of the university in civilian status.
And whenever we were on military duty together, he was General Rudder.
But I referred to him as Mr.
Rudder.
I tell you, it had been just like sticking a sword in me to have said Earl to him.
Even though you had fine relations?
Oh, absolutely.
I had a great respect for him.
And, you know, what he told me, I took for the gospel truth.
But I couldn't call him Earl.
I had never called a superior in the military by first name.
He was always Colonel, General, Major.
And I called him my boss.
Every, I never called him anything but Mr. Lane.
He was Mr. as far as I was concerned.
And I couldn't call him Earl at all.
He had a lot of my peers that were sort of on my level in other areas.
I called him O.D.
Butler.
I called him Jocko Roberts and all this sort of thing.
And he's my superior in rank and superior in age.
He was Mr. as far as I was concerned.
And that, I expect, probably changed the military.
Yeah.
Now, let's think back on your career for a minute.
What way do you think that the Corps, besides what you just mentioned, that the Corps helped your career?
Well, I think, of course appreciation for your fellow man.
Right.
And again, appreciation for being able to depend on somebody.
I think that whole lot stemmed from the military.
And being able to pick people that you could observe in their everyday operation for leaders in your organization.
So, in other words, you could generalize from the military to the highway.
That's right.
Find men that you could depend on in your civilian occupation or people who could become future leaders.
Yes, I think, I think, I think it gave you an ability to watch a person perform
and see how you handle men.
That's one of the things that the military always struck me is how you handle men.
And a lot of people can do things themselves, but they can't handle men.
They can't direct people.
And you see a great deal of that in the military and out there, even though
I was an officer in my senior year.
If a man was tabbed as company commander, then he was in charge.
And even though I was of a level with him, he was designated the man.
And he had the responsibility.
And what he told me to do, you know, I took it.
He was given that responsibility.
And that has spilled over in the highway business, or any other business, is that when an organization is set up and the man is appointed in charge, then that's the man that you look to.
And even though he may not be any more educated, he may not be any more immediately capable, he's got something that somebody said to him, you're it.
And that started in the military.
It started in the Corps.
Here's a man that's a platoon leader, here's a man that's a right guide or whatever, and you come on up, and here's the top man.
He's been tapped.
You could recognize that quality.
You could recognize it.
So those things started early in the Corps of Cadets.
Now, as you think back, do you think that there's any way in which the Corps of Cadets might have hindered your career in any way?
I don't know how it would have been.
I sure don't know.
Here would be, this would be the only thing that I could see, and I can't call that an interest now, had I not gone in the military.
I don't know what my World War II status would have been.
Let's just say that I had not been called and I had not been drafted for some reason.
I had five more years of experience in my civilian occupation.
I might have been five years further up the ladder.
